<font color="#FF0000">FADING AWAY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 12 22:20:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Brothers<br><br>
Earlier this year I posted the following message on a friend's page.  At the time I believed what I had said.  Some have tried desperately to maintain the effort.  Progress is in the hands of the dedicated vets who refuse to be silent.  It is with those that I find my alliance.  There are some non-vets who support the effort and others who would see it fail.<br><br>
&quot;The links continue to be quality, informative, and without bias. Even with my own experiences from continuous tours from late 1969 through 1973 I am surprised at the loss of animosity and the growth of understanding of most concerned. I myself have experienced this maturity with age. It<br>
appears my fears that there would be no one to carry that torch for this country and mankind are now unfounded. I hope the seed planted continues to grow. Through efforts such as yours we will be ensured of the fertile environment for such things to happen. Thanks!&quot; <br><br>
The dialogue on this site has shown that the vet was a casualty in the war and the one asked to sacrifice everything for success.  Even after the war it is the vet who remains a casualty and is still expected to sacrifice to ensure closure.  Some have folded under this unreasonable request, but many others have excelled because they were survivors.  It is still the survivors who are expected if not required to carry their bothers who stumble along the way.  We have accepted this task without question.  We like our brothers from other foreign wars will continue to speak out in the hopes to be heard until there is no one left.<br><br>
The social giants that think little of us will then write history.  It is happening even before our passage.  We in our isolated world will not tell our stories to our children because we want to spare them the pain.  I have shared nothing with my family.  They are comfortable having their life untouched by the war.  Their children will never know.<br><br>
This comfort is what others ask of us.  We are the ones who are asked to quietly fade away.<br><br>
We as a group and as individuals intend to leave our mark on the world and earn our proper place in history.  Time is on there side not ours.  We must continue to refuse to be quieted.<br><br>
They continue to ask for reconciliation, or a common ground.   The sacrifice must be theirs.  We have made ours.<br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


